{{short description|chess puzzle that uses humor}} '''Joke chess problems''' are puzzles in [[chess]] that use [[humor]] as a primary or secondary element. Although most chess problems, like other creative forms, are appreciated for serious artistic themes ([[Grimshaw (chess)|Grimshaw]], [[Novotny (chess)|Novotny]], and [[Lacny]]), joke chess problems are enjoyed for some twist. In some cases the composer plays a trick to prevent a solver from succeeding with typical analysis. In other cases, the humor derives from an unusual final position. Unlike in ordinary [[chess puzzle]]s, joke problems can involve a solution which violates the inner logic or rules of the game. {{algebraic notation|pos=toc}}
==Self-solving problems== {{Chess diagram | tright | V. Ropke, Skakbladet 1942 |kl| |kd| | | | | |pl| |pl|pd| | | | | |pd| |pl| | | | | | | | | | | | |pd| | | | | | | |pl| | |pl| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | White to move, mate in 6. Can it be stopped? }} Some chess puzzles are not really puzzles at all. In the diagram, White is asked to [[checkmate]] Black in six moves. The joke in this case is that, by the rules of chess, White has no choice in the matter: the only legal moves available lead directly to the "solution": :'''1. d4 b5 2. d5 b4 3. axb4 a3 4. b5 a2 5. b6 a1=any 6. b7{{chessAN|#}}'''
[[Tim Krabbé]] provides other examples on his chess website.<ref>[http://timkr.home.xs4all.nl/chess2/diary_14.htm Examples] &ndash; see items 276, 267, and 265</ref> {{clear}}
==Offbeat interpretations of the rules of chess== {{Chess diagram | tright | |rd| | | | | | | |kd|pl|rl| | | | | | | | | | | | | |kl| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |Mate in 1 }} The [[rules of chess]] are fairly simple and clearly defined. Nevertheless, some composers have relied on ambiguities in the rules to create humorous puzzles. A typical example would be the position shown in the diagram on the right. According to chess legend, a composer stipulated "White mates in one move." It appears to be impossible, and now is, but formerly the color of the promoted piece was not specified, and the "solution" was for White to promote to a ''black'' knight on b8, thus depriving the black [[king (chess)|king]] of its only [[flight square|escape square]].
{{Chess diagram | tleft | Tim Krabbé, 1972 | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |pl| | | | | | |pd| | | | | | |pd| | | |pd| | |pd|pl| |kd|pl|pl|pd | |pl| | | | | |pl |rl| | | |kl| | |rl |Mate in 3 }} A more sophisticated example was composed by [[Tim Krabbé]] and relied on a loophole that existed in the definition of [[castling]]. In the diagram, White must mate in three moves. The solution begins '''1. e7''', then the main variations are:
{{unordered list|style=list-style-position:inside |'''1... Kd3 2. e8{{=}}Q gxf3''' (other moves allow Qe2#) '''3. 0-0-0#''' |'''1... Kxf3 2. e8{{=}}R{{chesspunc|!}}''' (an [[underpromotion]]), and now: ||'''2... d4 3. 0-0#''' ||'''2... Kg2 3. 0-0-0-0#!''' }}
In the last variation, White castles with his newly promoted [[rook (chess)|rook]], moving his king to e3 and the rook to e2. Under the rules of chess at the time, this move was arguably legal because the rook had not moved yet. Afterward, FIDE amended the rules to require that the castling rook must occupy the same ''rank'' as the king. {{clear}}
==Unusual piece placement or movement==
Some problems are notable for extremely unusual patterns of piece placement. For example, direct mates and especially [[helpmate]]s have been composed with the pieces in the shape of a letter or number, or even a tree.
===The "back home task"=== {{Chess diagram | tleft | M. Kirtley, ''The Problemist'' 1986 | | | |ql| | | | |pd| | | | | | | |pl|pl| | | |pd| | |rl| | | | |pl| | | |pd|pl| | |pd| |pl |nl| | | |bl|nl| | |kd|rd| | |bl|kl| |pl | | | | |rl| | | | Selfmate in 8 }} A more interesting example occurs in this 1st Prize winner by Kirtley, where the final position echoes a familiar pattern. Krabbé calls this problem the "back home task", as all eight white pieces retreat to their initial positions. He writes that "Strategy and deep themes are absent, Black only has forced moves, but it's one of the funniest chess problems I ever saw."<ref>[http://timkr.home.xs4all.nl/chess2/diary_15.htm Open chess diary] &ndash; see item 289</ref> White must [[selfmate]] in eight moves; i.e., he must force Black to checkmate White against Black's will. The solution is: :{{pad|1.5em}}'''1. Nb1+ Kb3 2. Qd1+ Rc2 3. Bc1 axb6 4. Ra1 b5 5. Rh1 bxc4 6. Ke1 c3 7. Ng1 f3 8. Bf1 f2#''' {{clear left}}
===The "caterpillar theme"=== {{Chess diagram | tright | G. Bridgewater, ''Chess'' 1936 |kd| | | | | | | |pl|pd| | | | | | | |pd| | | | | | | |pd| | | |bl| | | |pd| | | |kl| | | |pd| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |rl| | | | | | | | Mate in 6 }} Krabbé named the "caterpillar theme" for problems and studies where doubled or tripled pawns move one after the other. The diagram at the right shows a particularly silly example, with White forcing mate in six moves. The solution is: :'''1. Bb1 b2 2. Ra2 b3 3. Ra3 b4 4. Ra4 b5 5. Ra5 b6 6. Be4#
Krabbé wrote a whole article on the caterpillar theme, citing about ten examples.<ref>The article is not available via direct link, but it can be downloaded on the archives at http://www.chesscafe.com/ (krabbe08.pdf).</ref>
{{Chess diagram | tleft | W. A. Shinkman, 1887 |kd| | | | | | | |pl| | | | | | | |pl| | | | | | | |pl| | | | | | | |pl| | | | | | | |pl| | | | | | | |pl| | | | | | | |rl| | | |kl| | | | Mate in 8 }} The American composer William A. Shinkman (1847–1933) is famous for composing the problem in the diagram, with sextupled pawns on the a-file. As Krabbé writes on his website, "The solution, as it should be in a joke, is not difficult: '''1. 0-0-0 Kxa7 2. Rd8 Kxa6 3. Rd7 Kxa5 4. Rd6 Kxa4 5. Rd5 Kxa3 6. Rd4 Kxa2 7. Rd3 Ka1 8. Ra3#'''".<ref name="kuwait-immortal">{{cite web |url=http://timkr.home.xs4all.nl/chess2/kuwait.htm |title=The Kuwait Immortal |publisher=Xs4all.nl |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref>
The problem is "{{chessgloss|cook|cooked}}" (ruined, in the lingo of chess composition), however, because 1.Kd2 also forces mate in eight moves. But this problem was not intended to be a sound mate in eight, and was instead intended to be a [[proof game]] in 34 moves with seven consecutive captures by Black.<ref name="kuwait-immortal"/> {{clear}}
==Humour in more traditional chess problems== Humour is a component of some traditional themes, such as [[grotesque (chess)|grotesque]] and [[Excelsior (chess problem)|Excelsior]].
In 2004, Hans Böhm sponsored a chess composing tournament for humorous [[endgame study|endgame studies]]. The top two entries appear with solutions on Krabbé's website.<ref>[http://timkr.home.xs4all.nl/chess2/diary_15.htm Open chess diary] &ndash; see item 281</ref><ref>[http://timkr.home.xs4all.nl/chess2/diary_14.htm Open chess diary] &ndash; see item 276</ref>
==Non-chess chess problems== {{Chess diagram | tright | T. R. Dawson | | | | | |kd| |kl | | | | |pd| | | | | | | | | |pl|pl | | | | |qd| |nd|bl | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | White to play }} In this kind of problem, although the problem is posed as a standard chess problem, the solution has nothing to do with chess moves. An example is this problem composed by British composer [[Thomas Rayner Dawson]]. In the position in the diagram, Black had decided to resign (although it wasn't his turn). White advised his opponent not to give up so quickly. "But I am bound to lose, and there is nothing I—or you, for that matter—can do", said Black. But White insisted: "I'll bet you $100 that I can lose this game!" So the two made the bet and White actually lost. He did not resign, lose on time, or anything like that. How did he lose?<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.chessbase.com/post/chessbase-chrismas-puzzles-2014-solutions-2|title=ChessBase Chrismas Puzzles 2014 – solutions|accessdate=2015-09-07}}</ref> The solution is in the words: White did not lose the game (which is impossible in the diagram position, as the only legal moves are 1.g7+ Qxg7+ 2.hxg7#), but rather the bet.
